The Night the Data Didn't Lie

Case VF-GH-2024-CR-0089 | HIVE CONSULT Vehicle Forensics Training Suite


On the night of 18 April 2024, a pedestrian was fatally struck on the N1 Accra–Tema Highway near Nungua Junction and left for dead. Witnesses reported a pearl-white Toyota Land Cruiser LC300 fleeing east at high speed. CCTV at a nearby fuel station confirmed the plate — GW-3314-23 — registered to a Director at the Ministry of Works.

By the time investigators arrived at his Airport Residential home the following morning, the dashboard was clean, the fault codes were gone, and the man had already spoken to his lawyer. He had spent the night doing what he thought was thorough deleting his route, wiping his messages, clearing the diagnostic codes, inserting a USB drive for forty-four seconds before pulling it out again. He believed the vehicle remembered nothing.

The Toyota Entune IVI unit told a different story. The Event Data Recorder had captured every millisecond of the impact — 98 km/h, throttle at 62%, brake pressure at zero, front-left structural deformation, headlight destroyed. The dashcam had frozen a frame at 22:47:00 showing the road ahead blurred with impact, the speed locked at 98 on the HUD. The parking camera taken the following morning showed the front-left void where the headlight used to be. The receipt in the Media folder placed him at a hotel bar ninety minutes before, three covers, eight drinks, checkout at 21:52.

And in the Phone database, four deleted messages sat waiting with a single flag beside each one — `deleted=1` — intact, timestamped, unharmed. *"Something happened. I hit something near Nungua. Just drive pass don't stop."* Two minutes after the body hit the road.

The vehicle had remembered everything. It always does.

